445.amp%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Watch%20%7C%20Indians%2C%20Episode%205%3A%20Nalanda%20and%20the%20Decline%20of%20Buddhism%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cimg%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F04130030%2FScreenshot-2024-02-04-at-1.00.20%25E2%2580%25AFPM.png%5C%22%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EWatch%20previous%20episodes%20here%3A%201.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fhistory%2Findians-a-history-web-series-namit-arora%5C%22%3EA%20Brief%20History%20of%20a%20Civilisation%20and%20Why%20We%20Need%20to%20Know%20it%3C%2Fa%3E%20%7C%202.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fhistory%2Findians-the-aryans-and-the-vedic-age%5C%22%3EThe%20Aryans%20and%20the%20Vedic%20Age%3C%2Fa%3E%20%7C%203.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fhistory%2Fwatch-indians-episode-3-the-mauryans-and-megasthenes%5C%22%3EThe%20Mauryans%20and%20Megasthenes%3C%2Fa%3E%20%7C%204.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fhistory%2Fwatch-indians-episode-4-the-ikshvakus-of-andhra-pradesh%5C%22%3EThe%20Ikshvakus%20of%20Andhra%20Pradesh%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ENalanda%20was%20a%20Buddhist%20monastery%20founded%20in%20the%205th%20century%20during%20the%20Gupta%20period%20(319%E2%80%93543%20CE)%E2%80%94a%20creative%20age%20for%20literature%2C%20art%2C%20architecture%2C%20maths%20and%20science.%20Nalanda%20became%20the%20greatest%20centre%20of%20Buddhist%20learning%20in%20the%20world%2C%20lasting%20more%20than%20800%20years%20until%20the%2013th%20century.%20It%20attracted%20student%20monks%20from%20across%20Asia%2C%20including%20three%20from%20China%20whose%20travel%20accounts%20contain%20fascinating%20insights%20into%20the%20social%20life%20of%20India%20and%20academic%20life%20at%20Nalanda%20in%20the%205%E2%80%937th%20centuries.%20They%20describe%20urban%20life%2C%20laws%2C%20medicine%2C%20obsessions%20with%20purity%20and%20pollution%2C%20food%20taboos%2C%20untouchability%20and%20religious%20conflicts.%20They%20relate%20the%20rhythms%20of%20daily%20life%20at%20Nalanda%2C%20its%20curriculum%2C%20star%20teachers%2C%20academic%20debates%2C%20funding%20sources%20and%20more.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20this%20episode%2C%20I%E2%80%99ll%20also%20explore%20the%20many%20causes%20for%20the%20decline%20of%20Buddhism%20in%20India%2C%20starting%20in%20the%20second%20half%20of%20the%20first%20millennium.%20By%20the%20time%20of%20the%20Turko-Persian%20invasions%2C%20most%20Buddhist%20sites%20had%20already%20been%20abandoned%2C%20destroyed%2C%20or%20converted%20into%20Brahminical%20sites%20across%20much%20of%20India.%20Buddhist%20artifacts%20and%20texts%20were%20wiped%20out%20and%20Buddhism%20vanished%20from%20India%E2%80%99s%20public%20memory.%20By%20the%20early%20colonial%20period%2C%20Indians%20had%20even%20forgotten%20that%20a%20man%20called%20the%20Buddha%20had%20existed%20in%20their%20past!%20Only%20in%20the%2019th%20century%20did%20Indians%20rediscover%20Nalanda%20and%20their%20amazing%20Buddhist%20heritage%20through%20archaeology%2C%20texts%20that%20survived%20in%20foreign%20lands%2C%20accounts%20of%20Chinese%20and%20Tibetan%20monks%2C%20and%20other%20sources.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cdiv%3E%3Ciframe%20allowfullscreen%3D%5C%22allowfullscreen%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fembed%2FGKe4pENohWk%3Fsi%3DmoDZ_LXov6H8EbZP%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22560%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22YouTube%20video%20player%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22315%5C%22%3E%3Cspan%20data-mce-type%3D%5C%22bookmark%5C%22%3E%EF%BB%BF%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3EBelow%20is%20the%20transcription%20of%20the%20entire%20episode.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EHello%20and%20welcome%20to%20Indians.%20I%E2%80%99m%20Namit%20Arora.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EIn%20the%20previous%20episode%2C%20we%20looked%20at%20the%20Ikshvaku%20Kingdom%20that%20thrived%20in%20Andhra%20Pradesh%20about%201800%20years%20ago.%20Among%20other%20things%2C%20it%20was%20a%20centre%20of%20Buddhist%20learning%20that%20was%20soon%20followed%20by%20even%20bigger%20centres%20of%20Buddhist%20learning%20in%20Eastern%20India.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EThe%20greatest%20of%20them%20was%20Nalanda%20Mahavihara%2C%20which%20attracted%20students%20from%20all%20across%20Asia%2C%20especially%20China.%20In%20this%20episode%2C%20I%E2%80%99ll%20look%20at%20what%20it%20was%20like%20to%20be%20a%20student%20at%20Nalanda.%20Who%20funded%20it%20for%20800%20years%2C%20and%20why%20did%20it%20disappear%3F%20What%20did%20the%20foreign%20students%20think%20about%20Indian%20society%20and%20culture%3F%20And%20what%20caused%20the%20demise%20of%20Buddhism%20in%20India%3F%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EThe%20Rise%20of%20Nalanda%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3ENalanda%20was%20a%20Buddhist%20monastery%2C%20established%20in%20the%20early%205th%20century%20during%20the%20Gupta%20Empire%20(319%E2%80%93543%20CE)%2C%20whose%20kings%20were%20among%20its%20early%20patrons.%20The%20Gupta%20period%20was%20highly%20creative%2C%20with%20major%20accomplishments%20in%20literature%2C%20art%2C%20architecture%2C%20and%20science.%20It%20was%20the%20age%20of%20Kalidasa%2C%20the%20poet%20and%20playwright%3B%20Vatsyayana%2C%20author%20of%20the%C2%A0%3Cem%3EKama%20Sutra%3C%2Fem%3E%3B%20and%20Aryabhata%2C%20the%20mathematician-astronomer.%20The%20decimal%20number%20system%2C%20also%20known%20as%20the%20Arabic%20numeral%20system%2C%20likely%20arose%20then%2C%20as%20did%20some%20of%20the%20sublime%20rock%20art%20at%20Ajanta%20and%20Ellora%20near%20modern%20day%20Aurangabad.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3ENalanda%20outlasted%20the%20Gupta%20Empire%20and%20many%20others.%20It%20lasted%20about%20800%20years%20until%20its%20demise%20in%20the%2013th%20century.%20It%20was%20the%20greatest%20centre%20of%20Buddhist%20learning%20in%20the%20world.%20So%20great%20was%20its%20reputation%20that%20student%20monks%20came%20to%20study%20here%20from%20across%20Asia.%20Hundreds%20came%20from%20China%20alone%2C%20but%20also%20from%20Sri%20Lanka%2C%20Tibet%2C%20Japan%2C%20Korea%2C%20Sumatra%2C%20and%20Central%20Asia.%20They%20often%20undertook%20dangerous%20overland%20journeys%20across%20deserts%20and%20mountains%20that%20took%20years%20to%20complete.%20Many%20didn%E2%80%99t%20make%20it.%20So%20why%20did%20they%20risk%20so%20much%3F%20Because%20they%20had%20several%20motivations.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EWhy%20Foreign%20Students%20Came%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAt%20least%20since%20Ashoka%20in%20the%203rd%20century%20BCE%2C%20Buddhism%20had%20been%20spreading%20across%20Asia.%20The%20Kushan%20Empire%20(c.%2030%E2%80%93375%20CE)%2C%20which%20extended%20from%20Central%20Asia%20to%20north%20India%2C%20promoted%20it.%20Traders%20and%20missionaries%20took%20Buddhism%20to%20China%20over%20the%20silk%20road%20and%20the%20seas.%20Many%20Turks%20and%20Persians%20embraced%20it.%20In%20China%2C%20Buddhism%20initially%20found%20favour%20among%20the%20elites.%20But%20they%20lived%20far%20from%20its%20Indian%20roots.%20Poor%20translations%20of%20Buddhist%20scriptures%20did%20not%20satisfy%20them.%20Misunderstood%20and%20defamed%20by%20rivals%2C%20early%20Chinese%20Buddhists%20longed%20for%20authentic%20sources%20to%20guide%20their%20faith%2C%20institutions%2C%20and%20practices.%20So%20these%20monks%20travelled%20to%20the%20subcontinent%20(1)%20to%20acquire%20Buddhist%20scriptures%20and%20texts%2C%20(2)%20to%20learn%20from%20Indian%20masters%2C%20and%20(3)%20to%20visit%20the%20sites%20associated%20with%20the%20Buddha.%20So%20in%20China%2C%20%E2%80%98Go%20West%2C%20young%20man!%E2%80%99%20became%20a%20call%20to%20go%20to%20%E2%80%A6%20India!%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EThe%20travel%20accounts%20of%20three%20of%20these%20monks%20have%20survived%3A%20Faxian%20(or%2C%20Fa-Hien%2C%20c.%20337%E2%80%93422%20CE)%2C%20Xuanzang%20(or%20Hiuen%20Tsang%2C%20c.%20602%E2%80%93664%20CE)%2C%20and%20Yijing%20(or%2C%20I%20Ching%2C%20c.%20635%E2%80%93713%20CE).%20They%E2%80%99ve%20given%20us%20many%20quirky%20and%20telling%20details%20of%20social%20and%20academic%20life%20in%20India%20between%20the%205th%20and%207th%20centuries.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EWhat%20the%20Chinese%20Saw%20in%20India%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EIn%20terms%20of%20average%20living%20standards%E2%80%94of%20food%2C%20clothing%2C%20homes%E2%80%94the%20Chinese%20monks%20saw%20India%20and%20China%20as%20about%20on%20par.%20They%20noticed%20a%20lot%20of%20%E2%80%98countries%E2%80%99%2C%20or%20kingdoms%2C%20in%20the%20Subcontinent.%20Yijing%20reported%2030%20%E2%80%98countries%E2%80%99%2C%20Xuanzang%2070.%20They%20mostly%20encountered%20kings%20who%20were%20Kshatriya%2C%20Vaishya%2C%20Brahmin%2C%20or%20Buddhist%2C%20but%20a%20small%20minority%20were%20Shudra%2C%20and%20one%20ruler%20was%20even%20a%20queen.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EThey%20recorded%20a%20range%20of%20laws%2C%20punishments%2C%20taxation%2C%20foods%2C%20festivals%2C%20and%20customs.%20Faxian%20described%20a%20well-functioning%20civic%20hospital%20system%20in%20the%20cities%20of%20the%20Gupta%20Empire.%20These%20monks%20also%20passed%20by%20large%20tracts%20of%20forests%20full%20of%20wildlife.%20That%E2%80%99s%20no%20surprise%3B%20India%E2%80%99s%20population%20was%20only%20about%20five%20percent%20of%20what%20it%20is%20today.%20A%20very%20different%20world%20from%20ours!%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EIn%20the%207th%20century%2C%20Xuanzang%20noted%20that%20Indians%20were%20%E2%80%98very%20particular%20in%20their%20personal%20cleanliness%E2%80%99%20but%20did%20not%20seem%20to%20mind%20their%20public%20streets%20being%20filthy.%20Sound%20familiar%3F%20Yijing%20wrote%2C%20%E2%80%98the%20first%20and%20chief%20difference%20between%20India%20and%20other%20regions%20is%20the%20peculiar%20distinction%20between%20purity%20and%20impurity%E2%80%99.%20The%20upper-class%20Indians%20he%20met%2C%20including%20monks%2C%20obsessed%20over%20foods%20they%20saw%20as%20innately%20%E2%80%98pure%E2%80%99%20or%20%E2%80%98impure%E2%80%99.%20Their%20custom%20was%20to%20be%20served%20on%20individual%20plates.%20They%20neither%20shared%20dishes%2C%20nor%20ate%20leftovers.%20To%20be%20touched%20by%20someone%20while%20eating%20was%20polluting.%20Only%20the%20right%20hand%20was%20to%20be%20used%20for%20eating.%20Onions%20were%20considered%20impure%20and%20a%20cause%20of%20tummy%20aches%2C%20diseases%2C%20and%20bodily%20weakness.%20We%E2%80%99ve%20come%20a%20long%20way%20from%20that%20attitude%20to%20toppling%20governments%20if%20the%20price%20of%20onions%20isn%E2%80%99t%20right.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EThe%20Chinese%20accounts%20also%20reveal%20that%20in%20the%207th%20century%2C%20caste%20and%20endogamy%20were%20well-entrenched.%20Outcastes%20lived%20beyond%20the%20walls%20of%20towns%20and%20villages.%20They%20included%20butchers%2C%20fisherfolk%2C%20dancers%2C%20executioners%2C%20scavengers.%20They%20could%20only%20walk%20on%20certain%20designated%20tracks.%20Their%20status%20was%20so%20low%20that%20they%20could%20even%20eat%20impure%20foods%20like%20onions%2C%20garlic%2C%20and%20cattle%20meat.%20Manual%20scavengers%20had%20to%20announce%20their%20passage%20by%20striking%20sticks.%20If%20a%20%E2%80%98pure%E2%80%99%20person%20touched%20one%20of%20them%20by%20accident%2C%20he%20had%20to%20thoroughly%20wash%20himself%20and%20his%20clothes.%20In%20other%20words%2C%20the%20records%20of%20Chinese%20travellers%20reveal%20that%20untouchability%20was%20a%20firmly%20established%20practice%20in%20the%20seventh%20century.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EXuanzang%20on%20Prayag%2C%20Varanasi%2C%20Mathura%2C%20Ayodhya%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EXuanzang%20saw%20a%20river%20festival%20in%20Prayag%20similar%20to%20the%20Kumbh%20Mela.%20People%20had%20assembled%20at%20the%20confluence%20of%20the%20Ganga%20and%20Yamuna%20to%20wash%20away%20their%20sins.%20He%20saw%20a%20majestic%20statue%20of%20Shiva%20in%20Varanasi%2C%20and%20noticed%20that%20the%20town%20was%20full%20of%20Brahmins%20and%20their%20hundred%20temples.%20He%20was%20very%20impressed%20by%20the%20Ganga%2C%20calling%20it%20wide%20and%20blue%2C%20and%20its%20water%20%E2%80%98sweet%20and%20pleasant%E2%80%99.%20Imagine%20saying%20that%20today!%20Both%20Xuanzang%20and%20Faxian%20described%20Mathura%20as%20a%20Buddhist%20town%2C%20with%20thousands%20of%20monks%20residing%20on%20both%20banks%20of%20the%20Yamuna.%20Mathura%20had%20long%20been%20the%20most%20important%20centre%20of%20Buddhist%20art%20in%20north%20India.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EXuanzang%20also%20called%20Ayodhya%20a%20great%20centre%20of%20Buddhist%20learning%2C%20with%20a%20hundred%20monasteries.%20It%20was%20known%20for%20its%20Yogacara%20school%20of%20Mahayana%20Buddhism.%20Brahminism%20was%20less%20common%20in%20Ayodhya%2C%20and%20Lord%20Rama%20is%20entirely%20absent%20in%20his%20account.%20This%20shouldn%E2%80%99t%20surprise%20us.%20After%20all%2C%20the%20cult%20of%20Rama%2C%20or%20Ram%20Bhakti%2C%20arose%20centuries%C2%A0%3Cem%3Eafter%3C%2Fem%3E%C2%A0Xuanzang.%20%E2%80%98Ayodhya%E2%80%99%20itself%20was%20a%20name%20recently%20given%20to%20a%20place%20long%20called%20Saket.%20This%20was%20not%20the%20same%20Ayodhya%20that%20Valmiki%20had%20in%20mind.%20In%20other%20words%2C%20Ayodhya%20was%20mainly%20a%20Buddhist%20town%2C%20and%20Rama%20was%20neither%20a%20popular%20god%2C%20nor%20did%20he%20have%20anything%20to%20do%20with%20the%20city%20we%20call%20Ayodhya.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EThe%20most%20powerful%20ruler%20in%20India%20in%20the%207th%20century%20was%20perhaps%20Harsha%20of%20Kannauj%2C%20who%20Xuanzang%20praised%20profusely%20for%20his%20temperance%20and%20generosity.%20Harsha%20was%20a%20strong%20leader.%20He%20had%20driven%20out%20the%20dreaded%20Hunas%2C%20the%20invading%20tribes%20from%20Central%20Asia.%20Like%20Ashoka%2C%20he%20too%20had%20embraced%20Buddhism%20in%20mid-life.%20He%20built%20hospitals%20on%20major%20highways%20and%20provided%20free%20food%20and%20medicines%20for%20all%20travellers.%20Every%20fifth%20year%2C%20in%20a%20grand%20event%2C%20he%20donated%20all%20surpluses%20in%20his%20treasury%20to%20charity%2C%20including%20to%20religious%20institutions.%20Xuanzang%20travelled%20at%20least%20as%20far%20south%20as%20Kanchipuram%20in%20modern%20day%20Tamil%20Nadu%2C%20where%20he%20saw%20a%20hundred%20Buddhist%20monasteries%20and%20eighty%20Hindu%20temples.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EThe%20State%20of%20Ayurveda%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EYijing%20studied%20Ayurveda%20but%20was%20not%20too%20impressed.%20He%20judged%20Chinese%20medicine%20better%20than%20India%E2%80%99s.%20Historians%20of%20science%20tell%20us%20that%20by%20then%2C%20Ayurveda%20had%20been%20stagnating%20for%20centuries.%20The%20origins%20of%20Ayurveda%20go%20back%20to%20the%20ascetic%20and%20Sramana%20communities%20of%20the%20early%20first%20millennium%20BCE.%20It%20had%20once%20made%20great%20strides%2C%20especially%20in%20surgery%2C%20using%20rational%2C%20empirical%20methods.%20But%20this%20began%20changing%20with%20the%20growing%20embrace%20of%20%E2%80%98purity%20and%20pollution%E2%80%99%20in%20the%20late%20first%20millennium%20BCE.%20Many%20upper-caste%20healers%2C%20or%20vaidyas%2C%20who%20dominated%20formal%20medical%20education%2C%20cut%20back%20on%20working%20with%20the%20%E2%80%98unclean%E2%80%99%20body%20and%20its%20fluids.%20The%20Manusmriti%20even%20lowered%20the%20ritual%20status%20of%20physicians%20who%20came%20in%20contact%20with%20sick%20bodies.%20This%20attitude%20only%20deepened%20as%20Brahminism%20spread%20in%20the%20Subcontinent.%20It%20stalled%20Indian%20medical%20science.%20Without%20hands-on%20experiments%2C%20unscientific%20ideas%20and%20practices%E2%80%94based%20on%20bodily%20humours%20or%C2%A0%3Cem%3Edoshas%3C%2Fem%3E%E2%80%94began%20rising%20in%20Ayurveda%2C%20where%20they%20stubbornly%20remain%20to%20this%20day.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EImpressions%20of%20Nalanda%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EThe%20Chinese%20monks%20say%20a%20lot%20about%20Nalanda%20too.%20When%20they%20visited%20in%20the%207th%20century%2C%20its%20resident%20population%20was%20about%203000%20monks.%20Archaeologists%20have%20so%20far%20uncovered%20eleven%20monasteries%2C%20six%20temples%2C%20and%20a%20giant%20stupa%2C%20called%20the%20Great%20Monument.%20Each%20monastery%20had%20a%20rectangular%20courtyard%2C%20a%20veranda%20all%20around%20it%2C%20and%20dorm%20rooms%20stacked%20two%20floors%20high.%20Each%20floor%20had%2030%E2%80%9340%20rooms%2C%20and%20at%20least%20two%20monks%20shared%20each%20room.%20The%20courtyard%20had%20a%20brick%20oven%20for%20cooking%2C%20a%20well%20for%20water%2C%20and%20bathrooms%20with%20covered%20drains.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EEach%20monastery%20was%20run%20by%20a%20learned%20master%2C%20a%20sort%20of%20dean%2C%20along%20with%20a%20supporting%20faculty.%20These%20teachers%20lived%20with%20the%20students%20and%20enjoyed%20the%20most%20spacious%20rooms.%20Formal%20greeting%20protocols%20existed%20between%20students%20and%20teachers.%20Courtyards%20had%20podiums%2C%20from%20where%20teachers%20lectured%20to%20students%20seated%20on%20the%20floor.%20Each%20monastery%20had%20its%20own%20shrines%20to%20the%20Buddha%20and%20other%20gods.%20It%E2%80%99s%20clear%20that%20Buddhism%2C%20like%20Brahminism%2C%20had%20admitted%20many%20local%20folk%20deities%20in%20its%20pantheon%20in%20order%20to%20broaden%20its%20appeal%2C%20though%20Brahminism%20was%20far%20ahead%20in%20this%20game.%20The%20motif%20of%20amorous%20couples%20had%20become%20increasingly%20common%20on%20religious%20sites%3B%20it%20even%20appears%20in%20the%20temple%20art%20of%20a%20monastic%20institution%20like%20Nalanda.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EThe%20Chinese%20accounts%20describe%20the%20monks%E2%80%99%20daily%20walks%20and%20bathing%20routines%20in%20nearby%20ponds%2C%20their%20worship%20and%20cremation%20rites%2C%20the%20games%20they%20played%20and%20the%20meals%20they%20ate.%20The%20staples%20of%20their%20food%20were%20rice%2C%20barley%2C%20beans%2C%20cooked%20veggies%2C%20and%20roots%2C%20with%20ghee%2C%20honey%2C%20or%20spices.%20Mangoes%20were%20much-loved.%20On%20rare%20occasions%2C%20the%20monks%20even%20ate%20meat%2C%20as%20long%20as%20it%20came%20from%20an%20animal%20who%20had%20died%20naturally%20or%20in%20an%20accident.%20So%20while%20they%20did%20not%20commission%20animal%20slaughter%2C%20they%20were%20pragmatic%20enough%20to%20not%20let%20good%20nutrition%20go%20to%20waste.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3ECurriculum%20and%20a%20Culture%20of%20Debate%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAll%20candidates%20at%20Nalanda%20had%20to%20be%20at%20least%2020%20years%20old%20and%20pass%20a%20qualifying%20oral%20exam.%20Only%20the%20best%20got%20in.%20Nuns%20were%20admitted%20too%20but%20not%20much%20is%20known%20about%20their%20lives.%20All%20students%20studied%20grammar%2C%20logic%2C%20philosophy%2C%20theology%2C%20astronomy%2C%20and%20medicine.%20They%20studied%20two%20schools%20of%20Mahayana%20(Madhyamaka%20and%20Yogacara)%2C%2018%20schools%20of%20Theravada%20(or%20Hinayana)%20and%20after%20the%20seventh%20century%2C%20several%20schools%20of%20Vajrayana%2C%20a%20Tantra-inflected%20form%20of%20Mahayana%20that%20lives%20on%20in%20Tibet.%20Their%20curriculum%20lacked%20politics%2C%20maths%2C%20and%20physics.%20The%20main%20science%20they%20studied%20was%20medicine%2C%20which%20combined%20aspects%20of%20botany%2C%20zoology%2C%20and%20chemistry%20in%20the%20service%20of%20a%20practical%20end%3A%20curing%20and%20sustaining%20the%20human%20body.%20According%20to%20Xuanzang%2C%20%E2%80%98The%20day%20is%20not%20sufficient%20for%20asking%20and%20answering%20profound%20questions.%20From%20morning%20till%20night%20they%20engage%20in%20discussion%3B%20the%20old%20and%20the%20young%20mutually%20help%20each%20other.%E2%80%99%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EMany%20of%20the%20teachers%20were%20rockstar%20thinkers%20and%20philosophers%2C%20such%20as%20Dignaga%2C%20Dharmakirti%2C%20Shantideva.%20They%20investigated%20questions%20that%20resonate%20even%20today%3A%20How%20does%20the%20structure%20of%20language%20impact%20our%20understanding%20of%20the%20world%3F%20Does%20language%20correspond%20to%20an%20objective%2C%20mind-independent%20reality%3F%20On%20what%20grounds%20can%20we%20establish%20the%20truth%3F%20Their%20framework%20was%20largely%20atheistic%2C%20and%20they%20vigorously%20debated%20each%20other%20as%20well%20as%20non-Buddhists.%20According%20to%20the%20Chinese%20monks%2C%20the%20Buddhists%20invariably%20won%20all%20the%20philosophical%20debates%20held%20around%20the%20country%2C%20handily%20beating%20Brahmins%2C%20Jains%2C%20and%20others.%20We%20can%E2%80%99t%20rule%20out%20bias%20in%20their%20reporting%2C%20but%20their%20claim%20was%20correct%20in%20at%20least%20one%20grand%20debate%20that%20was%20organised%20by%20emperor%20Harsha%20in%20the%207th%20century.%20From%20other%20sources%20we%20know%20that%20the%20Buddhists%20won%20at%20this%20event%20and%20Xuanzang%20was%20one%20of%20their%20star%20performers.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EWas%20There%20an%20%E2%80%98Indian%E2%80%99%20Identity%3F%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EThe%20Chinese%20monks%20observed%20great%20cultural%20diversity%20in%20the%20Subcontinent.%20But%20as%20outsiders%2C%20they%20also%20saw%20an%20ethnic%20quality%20that%20distinguished%20its%20people%20from%20others.%20They%20used%20a%20single%20term%20for%20all%20people%20on%20this%20side%20of%20the%20river%20Sindhu%20(Indus).%20This%20term%20was%20%E2%80%98In-tu%E2%80%99%2C%20derived%20from%20%E2%80%98Sindhu%E2%80%99%2C%20which%20the%20Persians%20pronounced%20as%20%E2%80%98Hindu%E2%80%99.%20This%20was%20a%20non-religious%20term%20used%20for%20the%20entire%20population%20of%20the%20subcontinent%2C%20like%20the%20term%20%E2%80%98Indians%E2%80%99.%20Only%20in%20late%20medieval%20times%20would%20%E2%80%98Hindu%E2%80%99%20start%20referring%20to%20a%20specific%20religious%20identity.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EThe%20monks%20noticed%20many%20common%20cultural%20features%20across%20these%20kingdoms%2C%20especially%20among%20the%20elite%20followers%20of%20big%20religions.%20But%20the%20people%20had%20no%20broadly%20common%20identity.%20As%20Yijing%20wrote%2C%20Indians%20did%20not%20see%20themselves%20as%20one%20people.%20They%20neither%20had%20a%20name%20for%20their%20vast%20territory%2C%20nor%20for%20themselves%20as%20a%20whole.%20No%20one%20saw%20themselves%20as%20practising%20%E2%80%98Hindu%E2%80%99%20religion.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EThe%20truth%20is%20that%20most%20people%E2%80%99s%20identities%20were%20highly%20local%2C%20shaped%20by%20their%20language%2C%20tribe%2C%20caste%2C%20region%2C%20king%2C%20faith%2C%20folk%20belief%20or%20custom.%20The%20average%20religious%20chap%20would%E2%80%99ve%20been%20very%20surprised%20to%20be%20told%20that%20he%20practised%20a%20widely%20shared%20faith%20called%20Sanatan%20Dharma%20(%E2%80%98eternal%20religion%E2%80%99)%2C%20as%20Hindu%20nationalists%20began%20claiming%20in%20the%2019th%20century.%20The%20term%C2%A0%3Cem%3Esanatan%20dharma%3C%2Fem%3E%C2%A0has%20no%20such%20historical%20reality%3B%20it%E2%80%99s%20a%20product%20of%20the%20conservative%20Hindu%20revivalism%20of%20modern%20times.%20In%20fact%2C%20the%20very%20idea%20of%20an%20%E2%80%98eternal%E2%80%99%20religion%20is%20weird%2C%20given%20the%20immense%20historical%20change%20in%20the%20subcontinent%E2%80%99s%20religiosity%20over%20the%20last%203500%20years.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EA%20Network%20of%20%E2%80%98Universities%E2%80%99%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EIs%20it%20correct%20to%20call%20Nalanda%20a%20%E2%80%98university%E2%80%99%3F%20Yes%20and%20No.%20Yes%2C%20because%20it%20was%20a%20community%20of%20teachers%20and%20scholars%20striving%20to%20advance%20knowledge.%20No%2C%20because%20it%20admitted%20only%20Buddhist%20monks%20committed%20to%20celibacy%2C%20who%20came%20to%20stay%20for%20life%20rather%20than%20graduate%20with%20degrees%20and%20return%20to%20public%20life.%20But%20with%20this%20caveat%2C%20we%20could%20call%20it%20the%20earliest%20university%20in%20the%20world.%20In%20fact%2C%20Eastern%20India%20sprang%20up%20many%20other%20well-regarded%20institutions%20like%20Nalanda%2C%20for%20instance%2C%20at%20Uddandapura%2C%20Vikramashila%2C%20and%20Somapura.%20They%20all%20collaborated%20but%20were%20also%20rivals%20for%20prestige%20and%20funding.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EFunding%20for%20Nalanda%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EIt%20seems%20the%20monks%20at%20Nalanda%20had%20a%20simple%20yet%20comfortable%20life.%20But%20who%20paid%20for%20all%20their%20food%2C%20the%20buildings%2C%20the%20artwork%3F%20Mostly%20the%20royals%20and%20wealthy%20merchants.%20Some%20of%20the%20royals%2C%20including%20foreign%20ones%2C%20secured%20for%20Nalanda%20long-term%20rights%20to%20the%20revenue%20of%20nearby%20villages.%20Apparently%2C%20a%20hundred%20villages%20supplied%20rice%2C%20cereal%2C%20milk%2C%20butter%2C%20ghee%2C%20vegetables%2C%20and%20other%20produce%20to%20the%20monastery.%20For%20the%20monks%2C%20it%20was%20like%20a%20lifelong%20scholarship!%20But%20while%20this%20secured%20their%20livelihood%2C%20it%20also%20had%20major%20downsides%20%E2%80%A6%20and%20contributed%20to%20the%20decline%20of%20Buddhism%20in%20India.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EWhy%20Buddhism%20Declined%20in%20India%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EBuddhism%E2%80%99s%20decline%20had%20begun%20in%20the%20second%20half%20of%20the%20first%20millennium.%20Xuanzang%20had%20already%20noticed%20its%20slide%20in%20the%207th%20century%2C%20and%20that%20trend%20accelerated%20in%20the%20centuries%20ahead.%20I%20think%20there%20are%20five%20key%20reasons%20for%20the%20decline%20of%20Buddhism%20in%20the%20land%20of%20its%20birth.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EFirst%3C%2Fstrong%3E%2C%20there%20had%20long%20been%20a%20competitive%20and%20hostile%20dynamic%20between%20Brahminism%20and%20Buddhism%2C%20mainly%20over%20three%20things%3A%20funding%2C%20followers%2C%20and%20ideology.%20The%20Chinese%20monks%20have%20recorded%20frequent%20and%20often%20bitter%20conflicts%20between%20Buddhist%20monks%20and%20Brahmins.%20Xuanzang%20reported%20a%20failed%20plot%20in%20which%20500%20Brahmins%20had%20hired%20a%20killer%20to%20assassinate%20emperor%20Harsha%2C%20because%20they%20were%20jealous%20and%20resentful%20of%20his%20%E2%80%98excessive%E2%80%99%20patronising%20of%20Buddhism.%20Centuries%20earlier%2C%20the%20grammarian%20Patanjali%20had%20himself%20compared%20the%20animosity%20between%20the%20Brahmins%20and%20Shramanas%20to%20that%20between%20the%20snake%20and%20the%20mongoose.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3ESometimes%20kings%20took%20sides%20in%20these%20battles%20too.%20In%20the%206th%20century%2C%20the%20Hun%20ruler%20Mihirakula%2C%20a%20Shaivite%2C%20destroyed%20stupas%2C%20monasteries%2C%20and%20killed%20monks%20in%20the%20northwest.%20According%20to%20Xuanzang%2C%20Shashanka%20of%20Bengal%2C%20a%20Brahminical%20king%2C%20%E2%80%98slandered%20the%20religion%20of%20the%20Buddha%E2%80%99%20and%20raided%20and%20%E2%80%98cut%20down%20the%20Bodhi%20tree%E2%80%99%2C%20%E2%80%98burnt%20it%20with%20fire%E2%80%99%20and%20destroyed%20the%20monasteries%20around%20it.%20There%20are%20many%20such%20stories.%20In%20short%2C%20Brahminical%20hostility%20was%20a%20major%20factor%20in%20the%20demise%20of%20Buddhism.%20Their%20conflicts%20appear%20in%20sculpture%20too.%20For%20instance%2C%20in%20the%20site%20museum%20at%20Nalanda%2C%20we%20see%20Buddhist%20Tantric%20deities%20trampling%20Brahminical%20gods%2C%20like%20Trailokya%20Vijaya%20trampling%20Shiva%20and%20Gauri%2C%20or%20Aparajita%20trampling%20Ganesh.%20They%20come%20from%20Buddhism%E2%80%99s%20waning%20centuries%20and%20seem%20like%20desperate%20attempts%20to%20signal%20their%20religious%20superiority%20to%20lay%20people.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3ESecond%3C%2Fstrong%3E%2C%20in%20the%20early%20centuries%20of%20Buddhism%2C%20its%20clergy%20had%20earned%20its%20living%20by%20relying%20on%20common%20people%2C%20exchanging%20religious%20services%20for%20donations%20of%20food%2C%20clothes%2C%20or%20money.%20But%20centuries%20of%20royal%20patronage%20had%20reduced%20their%20dependence%20on%20ordinary%20people.%20As%20their%20needs%20were%20taken%20care%20of%20by%20the%20royals%2C%20the%20monks%20reduced%20their%20contact%20with%20the%20lay%20public.%20They%20no%20longer%20needed%20the%20public%20to%20earn%20a%20living.%20They%20began%20retreating%20into%20walled%2C%20gated%20monasteries%20and%20grew%20self-absorbed%20in%20their%20academic%20and%20personal%20quests.%20As%20they%20abandoned%20the%20public%2C%20the%20public%20returned%20the%20favour.%20Lay%20Buddhists%20who%20didn%E2%80%99t%20care%20much%20for%20abstract%20theological%20differences%2C%20began%20shifting%20to%20rival%20religious%20orders%20with%20similar%20modes%20of%20worship.%20So%20the%20funding%20by%20the%20royals%20turned%20out%20to%20be%20a%20very%20mixed%20blessing%20indeed.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EThird%3C%2Fstrong%3E%2C%20between%20the%207th%20to%2010th%20centuries%2C%20profound%20changes%20occurred%20in%20the%20Indian%20religious%20landscape.%20Like%20the%20rise%20of%20Brahminical%20orthodoxy%2C%20led%20by%20Adi%20Shankara%2C%20and%20the%20emergence%20of%20Bhakti%2C%20or%20mystical%20devotionalism%2C%20in%20south%20India.%20One%20could%20say%20that%20there%20was%20a%20big%20churn%20in%20the%20religious%20market%2C%20and%20more%20satisfying%20products%20were%20turning%20up.%20Buddhism%20was%20one%20of%20the%20losers%2C%20partly%20because%20it%20was%20a%20more%20sober%20and%20austere%20faith%2C%20and%20partly%20because%20Brahminical%20Hinduism%20had%20more%20cleverly%20appropriated%20folk%20beliefs%20and%20practices.%20It%20had%20embraced%20popular%20features%20of%20Buddhism%20too%2C%20such%20as%20monastic%20orders%20and%20stopping%20animal%20sacrifices%3B%20it%20had%20even%20declared%20the%20Buddha%20as%20the%209th%20Avatar%20of%20Vishnu.%20As%20a%20business%20major%20might%20say%20today%2C%20this%20reduced%20Buddhism%E2%80%99s%20USP%20%5Bi.e.%2C%20unique%20selling%20proposition%5D.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EFourth%3C%2Fstrong%3E%2C%20with%20declining%20followers%20for%20Buddhism%2C%20the%20kings%20of%20the%20period%20began%20shifting%20to%20an%20exclusively%20Brahminical%20ideology%2C%20and%20this%20set%20in%20a%20vicious%20spiral%20for%20Buddhism.%20Funding%20for%20its%20monasteries%20began%20drying%20up.%20Its%20last%20great%20royal%20patrons%20were%20the%20Palas%20of%20Bengal.%20They%20were%20followed%20by%20the%20Sena%20dynasty%20of%20Bengal%20in%20the%2012th%20century%2C%20whose%20Brahminical%20kings%20actively%20persecuted%20Buddhist%20monks.%20Many%20monks%20fled%20south.%20On%20the%20eve%20of%20the%20Turko-Persian%20invasions%20around%201200%2C%20Buddhism%20had%20vanished%20from%20everywhere%20except%20isolated%20pockets%20in%20eastern%20and%20southern%20India%20and%20the%20western%20Himalayas.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAnd%C2%A0%3Cstrong%3Efifth%3C%2Fstrong%3E%2C%20with%20Indian%20Buddhism%20already%20on%20life-support%20by%20the%20late%2012th%20century%2C%20the%20final%20blow%20was%20delivered%20by%20the%20Turks%2C%20who%20finished%20off%20its%20last%20few%2C%20barely-functioning%20monasteries.%20But%20even%20this%20was%20not%20as%20black%20and%20white%2C%20or%20as%20dramatic%2C%20as%20many%20think%20it%20is.%20The%20popular%20belief%20that%20Nalanda%20was%20destroyed%20by%20the%20invader%20Bakhtiar%20Khilji%20(in%20the%201190s)%2C%20is%20not%20supported%20by%20historical%20evidence.%20Nalanda%20was%20still%20going%20in%201234%E2%80%9336%2C%20patronized%20by%20king%20Buddhasena%20of%20Bodh%20Gaya%2C%20when%20Dharmasvamin%2C%20a%20monk%20from%20Tibet%2C%20studied%20there.%20Rather%20than%20a%20dramatic%20final%20end%2C%20Nalanda%20continued%20its%20long%20phase%20of%20decay%20and%20depopulation%20for%20decades%20after%20Khilji%E2%80%99s%20death%20(1206).%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EBuddhism%20Vanishes%20From%20Public%20Memory%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3ESo%20the%20decline%20of%20Buddhism%20had%20many%20causes%2C%20although%20both%20British%20colonisers%20and%20Hindu%20nationalists%2C%20for%20their%20own%20convenient%20reasons%2C%20blamed%20it%20on%20Turko-Persian%20invasions%2C%20which%20was%20in%20fact%20a%20minor%20cause.%20As%20Buddhism%20dwindled%20over%20time%2C%20its%20sites%20were%20either%20abandoned%2C%20destroyed%2C%20or%20converted%20mostly%20into%20Brahminical%20sites%2C%20and%20a%20minority%20into%20Islamic%20sites.%20Even%20the%20Mahabodhi%20temple%20in%20Bodh%20Gaya%20was%20turned%20into%20a%20Shiva%20temple.%20Buddhist%20texts%20and%20artifacts%20were%20wiped%20out.%20Except%20in%20the%20western%20Himalayas%2C%20Buddhism%20practically%20vanished%20from%20India%20and%20its%20public%20memory.%20By%20the%20early%20colonial%20period%2C%20Indians%20knew%20nothing%20of%20Ashoka%20or%20his%20edicts%20or%20the%20Sanchi%20stupa.%20It%E2%80%99s%20hard%20to%20believe%2C%20but%20Indians%20even%20forgot%20that%20a%20man%20called%20the%20Buddha%2C%20the%20founder%20of%20a%20major%20world%20religion%2C%20had%20ever%20existed%20in%20their%20past!%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EIt%E2%80%99s%20often%20said%20that%20ancient%20Indians%20were%20not%20interested%20in%20history%2C%20that%20their%20accounts%20of%20the%20past%20are%20inseparable%20from%20myth.%20Such%20accounts%20are%20indeed%20common%20but%20they%E2%80%99re%20not%20the%20whole%20story.%20Pali%20chronicles%20from%20Sri%20Lanka%20suggest%20that%20Indian%20Buddhists%20had%20a%20much%20stronger%20tradition%20of%20writing%20history%20than%20the%20Brahmins%2C%20so%20the%20loss%20of%20Buddhism%20was%20a%20major%20setback%20for%20Indian%20self-knowledge.%20And%20when%20Buddhism%20disappeared%20from%20India%2C%20its%20texts%20disappeared%20with%20it%2C%20leaving%20a%20deep%20Brahminical%20bias%20in%20the%20surviving%20records.%20It%20was%20only%20in%20the%2019th%20century%20that%20Indians%20rediscovered%20Nalanda%20and%20their%20Buddhist%20heritage%20through%20archaeology%2C%20texts%20that%20survived%20in%20foreign%20lands%2C%20the%20accounts%20of%20these%20Chinese%20monks%2C%20and%20other%20sources.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EBut%20Buddhism%20wasn%E2%80%99t%20the%20only%20casualty%20of%20the%20new%20political-religious%20churning%20in%20the%20latter%20half%20of%20the%20first%20millennium.%20Other%20profound%20changes%20were%20also%20happening.%20In%20the%20next%20episode%2C%20I%E2%80%99ll%20take%20you%20to%20a%20very%20different%20setting%20in%20central%20India%20%E2%80%A6%20the%20amazing%20temple%20town%20of%20Khajuraho%2C%20and%20a%20major%20historical%20site%20where%20Indians%20happily%20combined%20erotica%20with%20religion.%20See%20you%20next%20time!%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1707031865000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F04130030%2FScreenshot-2024-02-04-at-1.00.2